Hand Gesture Controlled Paint Application - Project Report
1. Problem Statement
Traditional drawing applications require physical input devices like mice, styluses, or touchscreens, creating barriers for users with motor impairments, those in sterile environments, or scenarios needing hands-free operation. The core problem addressed is enabling intuitive, contactless digital drawing using only hand gestures, making creative expression accessible without traditional hardware dependencies.

This matters because:

Democratizes digital art for diverse users

Enables novel interaction paradigms

Supports accessibility for motor-impaired individuals

Prepares for future gesture-based computing interfaces

2. Approach and Technical Solution
Core Architecture
The solution combines MediaPipe Hands for real-time hand tracking with OpenCV for canvas manipulation, implementing a gesture-driven drawing system:

text
Input: Webcam → MediaPipe Hand Detection → Gesture Recognition → Tool State Machine → Canvas Operations
Gesture Vocabulary
Two primary gestures control the entire interface:

Tool Selection: Index finger tip (landmark 8) hovers over toolbar → 0.8s dwell time

Draw Mode: Index finger PIP (12) raised >40px above middle finger tip (9)

Tool State Machine
text
IDLE → TOOL_SELECT (hover+time) → TOOL_ACTIVE → DRAW (finger up) → PREVIEW → CONFIRM (finger down)
Five tools implemented with distinct behaviors:

Line/Rectangle/Circle: Preview on frame → Commit to mask on release

Draw: Continuous stroke while finger raised

Erase: 30px circular mask restoration

Canvas Management
Dual-layer rendering prevents destructive drawing:

