3. Key Technical Decisions
1. Single-Hand Detection Only
text
hands.Hands(..., max_num_hands=1)
Rationale: Simplifies gesture recognition, reduces computational load, matches primary use case of single-handed drawing.

2. Threshold-Based Gesture Recognition
text
def index_raised(yi, y9):
    return (y9 - yi) > 40  # 40px threshold
Rationale: Simple, robust vertical distance avoids complex angle calculations, works across hand sizes.

3. Preview-Commit Pattern
text
# Preview on original frame (temporary)
cv2.line(frm, start, end, color, thick)
# Commit to persistent mask (permanent)
cv2.line(mask, start, end, 0, thick)  # 0=black=hide
Rationale: Provides visual feedback during drawing + undo capability via mask restoration.

4. Dwell-Time Tool Selection
text
if (ptime - ctime) > 0.8:  # 800ms hold
    curr_tool = getTool(x)
Rationale: Prevents accidental tool switches while hovering, visual shrinking circle provides feedback.

4. Implementation Challenges and Solutions
Challenge 1: Hand Tracking Stability
Problem: Jittery landmark detection caused erratic drawing
Solution:

High confidence thresholds: min_detection_confidence=0.6

Single-hand mode reduces ambiguity

Smooth coordinate tracking via previous frame positions

Challenge 2: Gesture False Positives
Problem: Middle finger movements triggered drawing accidentally
Solution: Strict vertical threshold (y9 - yi) > 40 instead of angle-based detection

Challenge 3: Tool Boundary Precision
Problem: Toolbar selection failed near edges due to finger width
Solution: 50px tool zones + x > ml margin exclusion: if x < max_x and y < max_y and x > ml

Challenge 4: Performance on Commodity Hardware
Problem: 30fps target with real-time processing
Solution:

Single-hand detection only

Efficient mask operations

ROI-based toolbar overlay

5. Critical Learnings
Gesture Design Principles
Simplicity scales: Two gestures control complex functionality

Visual feedback is essential: Shrinking circle, live previews, landmark drawing

Thresholds > machine learning: Simple distance metrics outperformed complex models for this use case

State machines beat conditionals: Clear TOOL_ACTIVE → DRAW → CONFIRM flow prevents race conditions

Computer Vision Insights
text
Landmark 8 (index tip) = primary interaction point
Landmark 12+9 delta = reliable gesture trigger
Mask operations = perfect for non-destructive edits
UX Patterns for Gestural Interfaces
Dwell time > rapid gestures for precision selection

Preview before commit builds user confidence

Proportional feedback (shrinking circle) shows progress

Spatial consistency (toolbar stays fixed) aids muscle memory

